    <fr:title text="Self-Adjoint">Self-Adjoint</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors />
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>A <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002G.xml" addr="FA-002G" title="Bounded Linear Operator">bounded linear operator</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> on a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002J.xml" addr="FA-002J" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> is self-adjoint if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A = A^*]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A^*]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003K.xml" addr="FA-003K" title="Adjoint Operator">adjoint operator</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Equivalently, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is self-adjoint if:</fr:p>
    <fr:p>
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\ \langle  Ax,y\rangle  = \langle  x, Ay\rangle }]]></fr:tex>
    </fr:p>
    <fr:p>for all vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> in the Hilbert space.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Self-adjoint operators are fundamental in <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0130">spectral theory</fr:link> and quantum mechanics. Key properties include:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>The eigenvalues of a self-adjoint operator are always real</fr:li>
  <fr:li>Eigenvectors corresponding to distinct eigenvalues are orthogonal</fr:li>
  <fr:li>Every self-adjoint operator has a spectral decomposition</fr:li></fr:ul>
  </fr:mainmatter>
